{{Infobox person | name = Albert Busuttil | birth_date = 1891 | birth_place = [[Sliema]], [[Malta]] | death_date = 1956 | death_place = [[Malta]] | occupation = [[Philosophy]] }}
'''Albert Busuttil''' (1891–1956) was a Maltese minor [[philosopher]]. In philosophy he was mostly interested in [[politics]] and [[labour rights]].<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. I, p. 60}}</ref><ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2011|pp=104–107}}</ref>
==Life== Busuttil was born at [[Sliema]], [[Malta]] in 1891. He studied at the Lyceum and at the [[University of Malta]], and later joined the [[Jesuits]]. He continued his philosophical studies in [[Jersey]], [[France]], and his theology in [[Posillipo]], [[Naples]], in [[Italy]], both centres of [[Jesuit]] teaching. He was ordained a priest in 1922. Afterwards, he taught [[ethics]] in [[Ireland]], and [[history of philosophy]] in [[Catania]], [[Sicily]]. In [[Malta]] he taught [[philosophy]], [[apologetics]], [[mathematics]], [[physics]], and [[sociology]]. Between 1928 and 1945 Busuttil was Prefect of Studies at [[St Aloysius' College (Malta)|St. Aloysius College]], [[Malta]].
During [[World War II]] (1939–45) Busuttil would go around cities and villages gathering people in public squares and introducing them to the [[Social teachings of the papacy|social teaching]] of the [[Catholic Church]]. After the war he was than especially close to workers who were part of the newly founded [[General Workers' Union (Malta)|General Workers Union]], particularly at the shipyards. To people like Busuttil, the main worry in those days was the infiltration of the [[communist ideology]] within the workers’ movement. In 1947 he was appointed Spiritual Director of the union, an office he held up till 1951. He died in 1956.
==Works== Busuttil brought together his philosophical erudition and prowess, and his interest in mass education, particularly of workers. To this effect, he published a large number of pamphlets – more than sixty – which could serve as pocket-guides to the themes he chose to deal with. Though adopting a popular style and common language, he backed any of his arguments with a philosophical line of reasoning. Amongst his most worthy of consideration to philosophy, and also the most representatives of Busuttil’s thoughts and style, are the following:
* 1945 - ''Dokumentazzjoni Nisranija-Kommunista'' (Christian-Communist Documentation).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. II, p. 131}}</ref> * 1946 - ''Dostoievsky: Habbar tal-Bolxevizmu'' (Dostoyevsky: The Harbinger of Bolshevism).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. I, p. 133}}</ref> * 1946 - ''That il-Hakma tal-Mingel u tal-Martell'' (Under the Yoke of the Sickle and Hammer).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. II, p. 204}}</ref> * 1946 - ''It-‘Test Case’ Jew Il-Kalvarju tal-Polonja'' (The Test Case or Polond’s Calvary).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. II, p. 212}}</ref> * 1946 - ''Il-Gwerra, il-Paci u l-Knisja'' (War, Peace and the Catholic Church).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. I, p. 212}}</ref> * 1946 - ''Responsabbiltajiet u Rikostruzzjoni Socjali'' (Responsibilities and Social Riconstruction).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. II, p. 139}}</ref> * 1946 - ''Zewg Gganti: USSR - USA'' (Two Giants: USSR - USA).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. II, p. 268}}</ref> * 1946 - ''Demokraziji u Partit'' (Democracies and Political Parties).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. I, p. 115}}</ref>
