'''Tirupattur Ramaseshayyer Venkatachala Murti''' (June 15, 1902 – March 1986) was an Indian academic, philosopher, writer and translator.<ref name="OCLC profile">{{cite web | url=http://classify.oclc.org/classify2/ClassifyDemo?search-author-txt=Murti,%20T.%20R.%20V.%20(Tirupattur%20Ramaseshayyer%20Venkatachala) | title=OCLC profile | publisher=OCLC | date=2016 | accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="VIAF profile">{{cite web | url=http://viaf.org/viaf/94691564/ | title=VIAF profile | publisher=Virtual International Authority File | date=2016 | accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref> He wrote several books on [[Oriental philosophy]], particularly [[Indian philosophy]] and his works included commentaries and translations of Indian and Buddhist texts. He was an elected honorary member of the ''International Association of Buddhist Studies'' (IABS),<ref name="Honorary Members">{{cite web | url=http://iabsinfo.net/about-iabs/honorary-members/ | title=Honorary Members | publisher=International Association of Buddhist Studies | date=2016 | accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref> a society promoting scholarship in [[Buddhist studies]].<ref name="International Association of Buddhist Studies">{{cite web | url=http://iabsinfo.net/ | title=International Association of Buddhist Studies | publisher=International Association of Buddhist Studies | date=2016 | accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref> ''Studies in Indian Thought: Collected Papers,''<ref name="Studies in Indian Thought: Collected Papers">{{cite book | url=https://www.amazon.ca/dp/8120813103 | title=Studies in Indian Thought: Collected Papers | publisher=Motilal Banarsidass | author=T. R. V. Murti (Author), Harold G. Coward (Editor) | year=1996 | pages=426 | isbn=9788120813106}}</ref> ''Central Philosophy of Buddhism''<ref name="Central Philosophy of Buddhism">{{cite book | url=http://www.uread.com/book/central-philosophy-buddhism-trv-tirupattur/9788121510806 | title=Central Philosophy of Buddhism | publisher=Munshir Manoharlal Publishing | author=Tirupattur Ramaseshayyer Venkatachala Murti | year=2003 | pages=372 | isbn=9788121510806}}</ref> and ''A Study of the [[Madhyamika]] System''<ref name="A Study of the Madhyamika System">{{cite book | url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/a-study-of-the-madhyamika-system/oclc/852127344 | title=A Study of the Madhyamika System | publisher=George Allen and Unwin | author=Tirupattur Ramaseshayyer Venkatachala Murti | year=1960 | pages=372 | OCLC=852127344}}</ref> are some of his notable works. The Government of India awarded him the third highest civilian honour of the [[Padma Bhushan]], in 1959, for his contributions to education and literature.<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web | url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | title=Padma Awards | publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India | date=2016 | accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>

Murti dedicates his 1955 work, THE CENTRAL PHILOSOPHY OF BUDDHISM, as follows: "To my revered teacher Professor S. Radhakrishnan".

